Certainly! Below is a simple HTML code snippet that creates a web app to stream the video from the provided URL. This includes embedded CSS for styling and JavaScript for any basic interactivity.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Stream Night of the Living Dead</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            min-height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #000;
            color: #fff;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        video {
            max-width: 100%;
            border: 5px solid #fff;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div>
        <h1>Stream: Night of the Living Dead (Remastered HD)</h1>
        <video controls>
            <source src="https://archive.org/download/NightOfTheLivingDeadHD/NightOfTheLivingDeadRemasteredHD.mp4" type="video/mp4">
            Your browser does not support the video tag.
        </video>
    </div>

    <script>
        const video = document.querySelector('video');
        video.addEventListener('error', function() {
            alert('Error: Unable to load video.');
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The structure includes a title, a header, and a video element to play the video from the source URL.
- **Embedded CSS**: The CSS styles the body to center the content, sets a background color, and styles the video.
- **JavaScript**: A simple error handler alerts the user if there's an issue loading the video.

To use this code, simply copy and paste it into a text file with a `.html` extension, and open it in a web browser. The video should stream directly from the provided link.
